vectorData.altText: 3. The vessels that usually rupture to cause a subdural hematoma are the ___________ __________.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That’s right! Cerebral veins cross the (normally potential) subdural space. When torn, the extravasated blood separates the arachnoid from the dura, forming a subdural hematoma.

Cerebral veins coalesce, then cross the arachnoid mater and the meningeal layer of the dura to empty into the dural venous sinuses. Where they cross the meningeal layer of the dura, the outer wall of the cerebral veins are fused to the meningeal layer of the dura, and seal off the CSF-filled subarachnoid space from the venous blood-filled dural venous sinus. 
Cerebral veins can tear at the point at which they fuse to the meningeal layer of the dura. In this scenario, venous blood accumulates in the plane between the meningeal layer of the dura and the arachnoid mater. As the pressure mounts with the accumulation of blood, it pushes the two layers apart and creates a pathological “subdural space”. This is a subdural hematoma. The subdural space is, under normal conditions,a “potential space”, because it onlyexists in a pathological scenario.

Arachnoid granulations are out-pouchings of arachnoid mater through the meningeal layer of the dura into the superior sagittal sinus. CSF is extruded into venous blood across the arachnoid granulations.
